item.title: AMD Processors
item.dc:creator: @tebuddy tebuddy
item.description:
@tebuddy wrote:

Open the case up, find your motherboard manual, or download everest and figure out what motherboard you have.

Unless you have an antique computer dealer near your, or someone on craiglist, then I doubt you will find another one locally without shipping.

A new cpu (especially one built in 2003) will not show you a performance increase, save your cash until you can buy a decent machine.

Read full topic

item.dc:creator: @tebuddy tebuddy
item.description:
@tebuddy wrote:

http://www2.shopping.com/xPF-ASUS-Terminator-A7VT400-Barebones

Are you sure thats your motherboard?

Instead of shopping around for a new old motherboard and processor (good luck btw), you would probably pay some ridiculous chinaman to ship it to you. Spend 300-400 bucks and build a new machine.

I usually buy from newegg, and they dont even stock socket 754 anymore.
